reviews.text: Unstaffed with partially open waiting shelters on both platforms, to which ramp access is provided. Trains only once an hour at best, and as all are provided by TransPennine Express the range of destinations is somewhat limited. Not ideal for those commuting into Middlesbrough, although at least it makes getting to Manchester Airport relatively easy and the modest car park is free to use. At time of writing, the platforms are also being lengthened, so it may be that in future the option of travelling to London on a Grand Central service will be available.

It's a small station, recently improved with the addition of a ticket machine. Parking is currently free which is a big plus, I hope it stays that way. There are no snack machines or waiting rooms, but there is a shelter where you can sit on cold metal seats to avoid the rain.
A basic railway station on the scenic Northallerton to Eaglescliffe Railway. Steam trains pass through from time to time.
Unmanned but well kept station (for example its gritted in winter). Car park can be full by 9am during the weekday.
